% ============================================================================
% NOTES ON FIELD USAGE
% ============================================================================
%
% REQUIRED FIELDS:
%   - title: Keep concise but informative
%   - author: Format as "First Last and First Last"
%   - year: Used for chronological sorting
%   - journal/booktitle: Publication venue
%
% HIGHLY RECOMMENDED:
%   - doi: Makes paper discoverable and citable
%   - abstract: 100-150 words describing your work
%   - pdf: Path to your PDF (upload to _assets/pdf/)
%
% DISPLAY FIELDS (Make your page more attractive):
%   - abbr: 3-5 letter abbreviation shown as badge
%   - preview: Image path (gif, jpg, png) shown next to entry
%   - selected: Set to {true} to feature on main page
%   - bibtex_show: Set to {true} to show BibTeX citation button
%
% IMPACT & SOCIAL:
%   - altmetric: Numeric ID from Altmetric (shows social media impact)
%   - dimensions: Set to {true} to show citation count badge
%   - google_scholar_id: ID for linking to Google Scholar
%
% CUSTOM TEXT:
%   - annotation: Add custom note (supports markdown like **bold** and *italic*)
%   - additional_info: Extra details shown below entry
%   - award: Recognition or honors
%   - note: Generic note field
%
% ============================================================================
% FILE ORGANIZATION TIPS
% ============================================================================
%
% 1. Group by publication type (@article, @inproceedings, @book, @misc)
% 2. Within each group, order by year (newest first)
% 3. Mark your best/most impactful work with selected = {true}
% 4. Always include doi if available (essential for GitHub page rendering)
% 5. Use pdf field to link PDFs stored in _assets/pdf/ directory
% 6. Create preview images (300x300px PNG/GIF) for visual appeal
% 7. Write compelling abstracts to increase citations
%
% ============================================================================